#. type: Content of: <guide><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:6
#, no-wrap
msgid "GnuPG Gentoo User Guide"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><abstract>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:22
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This small guide will teach you the basics of using GnuPG, a tool for secure \n"
"communication.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:34
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:36
#, no-wrap
msgid "What you will get in this guide"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:40
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This guide assumes that you are familiar with public-key cryptography,\n"
"encryption, and digital signatures. If this is not the case jump to <uri\n"
"link=\"#doc_chap7\">Public Key Cryptography</uri> or take a look at the\n"
"<uri link=\"http://www.gnupg.org/documentation/guides.html\">GnuPG \n"
"handbook</uri>, chapter 2, and then come back.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:48
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This guide will teach you how to install GnuPG, how to create your key pair, how\n"
"to add keys to your keyring, how to submit your public key to a key server and\n"
"how to sign, encrypt, verify or decode messages you send or receive. You will\n"
"also learn how to encrypt files on your local computer to prevent people from\n"
"reading their contents.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:58
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installation of required software"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:62
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"At a very basic level you need to <c>emerge gnupg</c>. Many aplications today\n"
"have some sort of support for gpg, so having <e>crypt</e> in your USE variable\n"
"is probably a good idea. If you wish to have an email client capable of using\n"
"gnupg you can use pine (<c>emerge pinepgp</c>), mutt (<c>emerge mutt</c>),\n"
"Mozilla Thunderbird (<c>emerge thunderbird</c>), evolution (evolution is\n"
"a GNOME Microsoft Outlook work alike) and KDE's own KMail.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:71
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>Kgpg</c> might interest you if you use KDE. This small program allows you to\n"
"generate key pairs, import keys from ASCII files, sign imported keys, export\n"
"keys and a few more features.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:81
#, no-wrap
msgid "Generating your key and adding keys to your public keyring"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:83
#, no-wrap
msgid "Creating your key"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:87
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To create your key, just run <c>gpg --gen-key</c>. The first time you run it,\n"
"it will create some directories; run it again to create the keys:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:91
#, no-wrap
msgid "key generation process"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:92
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>gpg --gen-key</i>\n"
"gpg (GnuPG) 1.0.7; Copyright (C) 2002 Free Software Foundation, Inc.\n"
"This program comes with ABSOLUTELY NO WARRANTY.\n"
"This is free software, and you are welcome to redistribute it\n"
"under certain conditions. See the file COPYING for details.\n"
"\n"
"Please select what kind of key you want:\n"
"   (1) RSA and RSA (default)\n"
"   (2) DSA and Elgamal\n"
"   (3) DSA (sign only)\n"
"   (4) RSA (sign only)\n"
"   Your selection? <i>1</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:107
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Here you can choose the type of key you want to use. Most users will go for the\n"
"default RSA and RSA. Next is the key size - remember that bigger is better\n"
"but don't use a size larger than 2048 with DSA/ElGamal keys. Generally 2048 is \n"
"more than enough for normal email.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:114
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"After size comes the expiration date. Here smaller is better, but most users can\n"
"go for a key that never expires or to something like 2 or 3 years.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:118
#, no-wrap
msgid "Choosing key size"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:119
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"RSA keypair will have 1024 bits.\n"
"RSA keys may be between 1024 and 4096 bits long.\n"
"    What keysize do you want? (2048) <i>2048</i>\n"
"Requested keysize is 2048 bits       \n"
"Please specify how long the key should be valid.\n"
"         0 = key does not expire\n"
" &lt;n&gt;= key expires in n days\n"
" &lt;n&gt;w = key expires in n weeks\n"
" &lt;n&gt;m = key expires in n months\n"
" &lt;n&gt;y = key expires in n years\n"
" Key is valid for? (0) <i>0</i>\n"
"Key does not expire at all\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:134
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now it is time to enter some personal information about yourself. If you are\n"
"going to send your public key to other people you have to use your real email\n"
"address here.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:139
#, no-wrap
msgid "Entering user information"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:140
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Is this correct (y/n)? <i>y</i>\n"
"                        \n"
"GnuPG needs to construct a user ID to identify your key.\n"
"\n"
"Real name: <i>John Doe</i>\n"
"Email address: <i>john@nowhere.someplace.flick</i>\n"
"Comment: <i>The Real John Doe</i>\n"
"You selected this USER-ID:\n"
"\"John Doe (The Real John Doe) &lt;john@nowhere.someplace.flick&gt;\"\n"
"\n"
"Change (N)ame, (C)omment, (E)mail or (O)kay/(Q)uit? <i>O</i> \n"
"You need a Passphrase to protect your secret key.    \n"
"\n"
"Enter passphrase: \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:157
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now enter your key passphrase twice. It is a good idea to use a strong password.\n"
"If someone ever gets hold of your private key and cracks your password, they\n"
"will be able to send messages signed by \"you\", making everyone believe the mails\n"
"were sent by you.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:164
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Next, GnuPG will generate your key. Moving the mouse or having a mp3 playing in\n"
"the background will help speed up the process because it generates random data.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:171
#, no-wrap
msgid "Generating a revocation certificate"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><impo>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:175
#, no-wrap
msgid "This part is very important and you must do it <e>NOW</e>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:179
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"After creating your keys you should create a revocation certificate. Doing this\n"
"allows you to revoke your key in case something nasty happens to your key\n"
"(someone gets hold of your key/passphrase).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:184
#, no-wrap
msgid "Generating revoke certificate"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:185
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>gpg --list-keys</i>\n"
"/home/humpback/.gnupg/pubring.gpg\n"
"---------------------------------\n"
"pub  1024D/75447B14 2002-12-08 John Doe (The Real John Doe) &lt;john@nowhere.someplace.flick&gt;\n"
"sub  2048g/96D6CDAD 2002-12-08\n"
"\n"
"$ <i>gpg --output revoke.asc --gen-revoke 75447B14</i>\n"
"\n"
"sec  1024D/75447B14 2002-12-08   John Doe (The Real John Doe) &lt;john@nowhere.someplace.flick&gt;\n"
"\n"
"Create a revocation certificate for this key? <i>y</i>\n"
"Please select the reason for the revocation:   \n"
"  0 = No reason specified\n"
"  1 = Key has been compromised\n"
"  2 = Key is superseded\n"
"  3 = Key is no longer used\n"
"  Q = Cancel\n"
"(Probably you want to select 1 here)\n"
"Your decision? <i>1</i>\n"
"Enter an optional description; end it with an empty line:\n"
"&gt; <i>Someone cracked me and got my key and passphrase</i>\n"
"&gt;\n"
"Reason for revocation: Key has been compromised\n"
"Someone cracked me and got my key and passphrase\n"
"Is this okay? <i>y</i>\n"
"\n"
"You need a passphrase to unlock the secret key for\n"
"user: \"John Doe (The Real John Doe) &lt;john@nowhere.someplace.flick&gt;\"\n"
"1024-bit DSA key, ID 75447B14, created 2002-12-08\n"
"\n"
"ASCII armored output forced.\n"
"Revocation certificate created.\n"
"\n"
"Please move it to a medium which you can hide away; if Mallory gets\n"
"access to this certificate he can use it to make your key unusable.\n"
"It is smart to print this certificate and store it away, just in case\n"
"your media become unreadable.  But have some caution:  The print system of\n"
"your machine might store the data and make it available to others!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:226
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>gpg --list-keys</c> command lists keys in your public keyring. You may\n"
"use it to see the ID of your key so that you can create the revocation \n"
"certificate. Now it is a good idea to copy all the .gnupg directory and the \n"
"revocation certificate (in ASCII armor - <path>revoke.asc</path>) to some \n"
"secure medium (two floppy's or a CD-R you store in safe location). Remember \n"
"that <path>revoke.asc</path> can be used to revoke your keys and make them \n"
"unusable in the future.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><note>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:236
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you have several email addresses that you would like to use with this\n"
"key, you can run <c>gpg --edit-key YOUR_ID</c> and then use the <c>adduid</c>\n"
"command. It will ask you for the name, email and comment of the second ID you\n"
"will be using.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:245
#, no-wrap
msgid "Exporting keys"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:249
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To export your key, you type <c>gpg --armor --output john.asc --export\n"
"john@nowhere.someplace.flick</c>. You can almost always use the key ID or\n"
"something that identifies the key (here we used an email address). John now has \n"
"a <path>john.asc</path> that he can send his friends, or place on his web page \n"
"so that people can communicate safely with him.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:259
#, no-wrap
msgid "Importing keys"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:263
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To add files to your public keyring, you must first import it, then check the\n"
"key fingerprint. After you have verified the fingerprint you should validate it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><note>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:268
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You should be careful when verifying keys. This is one of the weak points of\n"
"public key cryptography.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:273
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now we will be adding Luis Pinto's (a friend of mine) public key to our public\n"
"keyring. After giving him a call and asking him for his key fingerprint, I\n"
"compare the fingerprint with the output of the <c>fpr</c> command. As the key is\n"
"authentic, I add it to the public keyring. In this particular case, Luis's key\n"
"will expire in 2003-12-01 so I am asked if I want my signature on his key to\n"
"expire at the same time.\n"
msgstr ""

