#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:426
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using a GPG Agent"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:428
#, no-wrap
msgid "What is a GPG Agent?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:432
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Sometimes working with certain applications requires you to use your GPG key\n"
"very frequently, which means that you have to type your passphrase a lot of\n"
"times. Several applications used to support a passphrase caching mechanism to\n"
"make life easier for users. However, this disallowed sharing this cache across\n"
"programs (how secure would that be?) and forced applications to reinvent the\n"
"wheel over and over again.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:441
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"A GPG agent is a separate application that GPG uses to cache the passphrase in\n"
"a standard and secure way. It allows applications to use GPG concurrently: if\n"
"you enter your passphrase while working in one application, the other\n"
"application can work with GPG without reiterating the request for the\n"
"passphrase to unlock the key - if the GPG agent is configured to allow so, of\n"
"course.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:450
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Gentoo provides a few GPG agent applications. The <c>app-crypt/gnupg</c>\n"
"package contains what could be considered the reference one, and will be the\n"
"one we'll use in this document.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:458
#, no-wrap
msgid "Configuring gpg-agent and pinentry"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:462
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"GnuPG includes <c>gpg-agent</c> and <c>pinentry</c>. <c>pinentry</c> is the\n"
"helper application that gpg-agent uses to request the passphrase in a graphical\n"
"window. It comes in three flavors: it can popup a window using the gtk+, Qt, or\n"
"curses library (depending on your USE flags in\n"
"<path>/etc/portage/make.conf</path>). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:470
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you installed <c>pinentry</c> with more than one popup window type, you can\n"
"choose between them with <c>eselect-pinentry</c>:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:474
#, no-wrap
msgid "Switching popup windows"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:475
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>eselect pinentry list</i>\n"
"Available pinentry implementations:\n"
"  [1]   pinentry-gtk-2 *\n"
"  [2]   pinentry-curses\n"
"  [3]   pinentry-qt4\n"
"\n"
"# <i>eselect pinentry set 1</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:485
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now create a file called <path>~/.gnupg/gpg-agent.conf</path> and enter the\n"
"following lines which define the default timeout of the passphrase (e.g. 30\n"
"minutes) and the application to be called for when the passphrase should be\n"
"retrieved the first time (e.g. the gtk+ version of pinentry).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:491
#, no-wrap
msgid "Editing ~/.gnupg/gpg-agent.conf"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:492
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"pinentry-program /usr/bin/pinentry-gtk-2\n"
"no-grab\n"
"default-cache-ttl 1800\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:498
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now configure GnuPG to use an agent when appropriate. Edit\n"
"<path>~/.gnupg/gpg.conf</path> and add the following line:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:502
#, no-wrap
msgid "Configuring GnuPG to use a GPG Agent"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:503
#, no-wrap
msgid "use-agent\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:507
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now your system is (almost) set to use the GPG agent.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:513
#, no-wrap
msgid "Automatically Starting the GPG Agent"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:517
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you use KDE as your graphical environment, edit\n"
"<path>/etc/kde/startup/agent-startup.sh</path> and uncomment the following\n"
"(system-wide) or <path>~/.kde4/env/gpg-agent.sh</path> (local user) and add the\n"
"following command to it to have KDE automatically starting the GPG agent:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:523
#, no-wrap
msgid "Make KDE automatically start the GPG agent"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:524
#, no-wrap
msgid "eval \"$(gpg-agent --daemon)\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:528
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Additionally, uncomment the following in\n"
"<path>/etc/kde/shutdown/agent-shutdown.sh</path> (system-wide) or add it to\n"
"<path>~/.kde4/shutdown/gpg-agent.sh</path> (local user):\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:533
#, no-wrap
msgid "Make KDE shut down the GPG agent"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:534
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"if [ -n \"${GPG_AGENT_INFO}\" ]; then\n"
"  kill $(echo ${GPG_AGENT_INFO} | cut -d':' -f 2) &gt;/dev/null 2&gt;&amp;1\n"
"fi\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:540
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you use a different graphical environment, put that line (the same one as\n"
"mentioned above) in <path>~/.xinitrc</path> (if you use <c>startx</c>) or\n"
"<path>~/.xsession</path> (if you use XDM/GDM/KDM/...).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:550
#, no-wrap
msgid "Working with documents"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:552
#, no-wrap
msgid "Encrypting and signing"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:556
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Let's say that you have a file that you wish to send Luis. You can encrypt\n"
"it, sign it, or encrypt it and sign it. Encrypting means that only Luis will be\n"
"able to open it. The signature tells Luis that it was really you who created the\n"
"file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:563
#, no-wrap
msgid "The next three commands will do just that, encrypt, sign and encrypt/sign.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:566
#, no-wrap
msgid "Encrypting and Signing files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:567
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>gpg --output doc.gpg --encrypt --recipient lmpinto@dei.uc.pt doc_to_encrypt</i>\n"
"$ <i>gpg --output doc.gpg --sign --recipient lmpinto@dei.uc.pt doc_to_sign</i>\n"
"$ <i>gpg --output doc.gpg --encrypt --sign --recipient lmpinto@dei.uc.pt doc_to_encrypt_and_sign</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:573
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This will create binary files. If you wish to create ASCII files, just add a\n"
"<c>--clearsign</c> to the beginning of the command.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:580
#, no-wrap
msgid "Decrypting and verifying signatures"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:584
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Suppose that you have received a file which is encrypted to you. The command\n"
"to decrypt it is <c>gpg --output document --decrypt encrypted_doc.gpg</c>. This\n"
"will decrypt the document and verify the signature (if there is one).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:592
#, no-wrap
msgid "Encrypting and decrypting without keys"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:596
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"It is also possible to encrypt files using passwords instead of keys. Well, the\n"
"password itself will function as the key - it will be used as a <e>symmetric\n"
"cypher</e>. You can encrypt the file using <c>gpg</c>'s <c>--symmetric</c>\n"
"argument; decrypting uses the same command as we talked about before.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:602
#, no-wrap
msgid "Encrypting files using a password"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:603
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>gpg --output document.gpg --symmetric document</i>\n"
"<comment>(GnuPG will ask for a passphrase and a passphrase verification)</comment>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:610
#, no-wrap
msgid "Advanced Features"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:614
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There are some nice advanced features in GnuPG. To find them, open the\n"
"<path>~/.gnupg/gpg.conf</path> file. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:618
#, no-wrap
msgid "~/.gnupg/gpg.conf"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:619
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"#keyserver x-hkp://subkeys.pgp.net\n"
"#keyserver-options auto-key-retrieve include-disabled include-revoked\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:624
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Search for the above two lines and uncomment them. With this any time GnuPG\n"
"needs to check a signature and it does not find the public key on the local\n"
"keyring it will contact the key server at <uri \n"
"link=\"http://subkeys.pgp.net:11371/\">subkeys.pgp.net</uri> and will try to fetch\n"
"it from there.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:632
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Another nice command is <c>gpg --refresh-keys</c>. This will contact the\n"
"keyserver defined in the options file and refresh public keys in your local key\n"
"ring from there, searching for revoked keys, new IDs, and new signatures on\n"
"keys.  You should probably run this once or twice a month so that if someone\n"
"revokes his key you will be notified.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:644
#, no-wrap
msgid "GnuPG interfaces"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:646
#, no-wrap
msgid "About email signatures"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:650
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"95% of the time you will use GnuPG with email, signing/encrypting your outgoing\n"
"messages and reading signed/encrypted messages. So it is only fair that I talk\n"
"about that first.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:656
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There are two ways two sign/encrypt a email with GnuPG, the old way and the new\n"
"way :). In the old way messages would appear in plain text, with no possible\n"
"formatting and attached files would be unsigned/unencrypted. Here is an example\n"
"of a message signed the old way:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:662
#, no-wrap
msgid "A plain text signature"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:663
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"-----BEGIN PGP SIGNED MESSAGE-----\n"
"Hash: SHA1\n"
"\n"
"Test message\n"
"\n"
"-----BEGIN PGP SIGNATURE-----\n"
"Version: PGPfreeware 6.5.8 for non-commercial use\n"
"\n"
"iQA/AwUBP8461jMX0745gR7AEQIEOwCg011GbufXO3ED3FkLWXmfzg7xm1cAoJD0\n"
"0EU3Kd2EKNCqataEqM5qjpPs\n"
"=LchZ\n"
"-----END PGP SIGNATURE-----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:678
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Messages this way are no good in today's world, where we have nice GUIs and\n"
"email readers that understand html.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:683
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To solve this an addition to the MIME (Multipurpose Internet Mail Extensions)\n"
"was created. This adds a field to the email that tells the mail reader that the \n"
"full content of the message is signed and/or encrypted. The problem with this \n"
"is that not all mail readers support this. And some even mess up the content; \n"
"Microsoft's Outlook is famous for not working with this.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:693
#, no-wrap
msgid "Kgpg"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:697
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Kgpg is a nice GUI for GnuPG. In the main screen you can paste the text that\n"
"you wish to sign or encrypt, and you can also paste the ASCII armored text that\n"
"you which to decrypt.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:705
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In this image you can see the Kgpg main window with ASCII armored and encrypted\n"
"text pasted into it. From here you can decrypt it (you will have to provide your\n"
"password), encrypt other files, paste new text to sign....\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:713
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now you can see the key managing window. From here we see our good key for John\n"
"Doe. The two trusted keys for Gustavo and Luis, and the untrusted key for Daniel\n"
"Robbins (I still have not given him a call to check his fingerprint :)).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:721
#, no-wrap
msgid "Seahorse"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:725
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Seahorse aims to be a GnuPG GUI interface for the Gnome desktop. The software \n"
"has been evolving fast, but it still lacks many important features that can be \n"
"found in Kgpg or the command line version.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:733
#, no-wrap
msgid "KMail"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:737
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you have the <c>crypt</c> USE flag set, KMail will be compiled with gpg\n"
"support, and will be able to encrypt and decrypt inline PGP mails automatically\n"
"as well as encrypting OpenPGP/MIME mails. If you want to decrypt OpenPGP/MIME\n"
"mails as well (which you probably want) you need to have a running GPG agent\n"
"(see <uri link=\"#gpg-agent\">Using a GPG Agent</uri>).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:745
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You can verify if KMail is properly configured by going to <c>Settings</c>,\n"
"<c>Configure KMail</c>, <c>Security</c>, <c>Crypto Backends</c>. You should see\n"
"a GpgME-based backend listed and you should be able to fill the OpenPGP\n"
"checkbox. If it is listed but grayed out, click on <c>Rescan</c>. If the\n"
"GpgME-based backend remains grayed out, KMail is not working properly.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:753
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you still are unable to get KMail to behave, please see the \n"
"<uri link=\"http://kmail.kde.org/kmail-pgpmime-howto.html\">KMail PGP HowTo</uri> \n"
"page for more information.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:761
#, no-wrap
msgid "Claws-Mail"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:765
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This mail reader is <e>very</e> fast with big mailboxes, has all the nice\n"
"features one wants in mail readers and works pretty well with gpg. The only\n"
"problem is that it does not work with the old PGP signatures, so when you\n"
"receive those kind of mails you have to hand check the signatures.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:772
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To use your gpg key with Claws-Mail just go to the account configuration and\n"
"select the privacy tab. Once there just choose which key to use, probably most \n"
"users will go with the default key.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:782
#, no-wrap
msgid "Public Key Cryptography"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:784
#, no-wrap
msgid "Basic Public Key Cryptography"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:788
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The concept of public key cryptography was originally devised by Whitfield\n"
"Diffie and Martin Hellman in 1976. When I first heard the words \"public key\" and\n"
"\"cryptography\" in the same sentence back in '93 I thought to myself that it\n"
"would be impossible to do such a thing. In those days there was no Internet\n"
"(well there was, but not for me) so I went to the public library and asked for\n"
"books on Cryptography. I must say that I was 16 at the time so the clerk there\n"
"looked to me in astonishment and brought me a book for children on substitution\n"
"cyphers (those where you change a letter for another like the famous Caesar\n"
"Cypher or ROT-13 (Tragbb Ebpxf, naq lbh xabj vg vf tbbq orpnhfr lbh ner ernqvat\n"
"guvf qbp.), (<c>emerge rotix</c> if you cannot read the preceding text)). I was\n"
"very upset with this and started to search for more info. It is good to have\n"
"mathematicians in the family, because as soon as I talked to one of them I was\n"
"introduced to a new world.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:804
#, no-wrap
msgid "And now a bit of mathematics: \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:807
#, no-wrap
msgid "Mathematical Concepts"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:808
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Definitions:\n"
"\n"
"1- A prime number is a positive integer number greater than one that is only\n"
"divisible by 1 and itself (the remainder of the division is 0).\n"
"The first 8 prime numbers are 2,3,5,7,11,13,17,19\n"
"\n"
"Theorem (No proof here)\n"
"1- For any non prime positive integer it is possible to break it as the product\n"
"of prime numbers, and that product is unique.\n"
"4=2*2\n"
"6=2*3\n"
"8=2*4=2*2*2\n"
"10=2*5\n"
"12=2*6=2*2*3\n"
"\n"
"\"Facts\":\n"
"1- It is mathematically easy to multiply two large integers\n"
"2- It is hard to find the prime factors of a given positive integer.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:829
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If I give you the number 35 and I tell you that this number is the product of\n"
"two prime numbers it is easy to find that it was 5 and 7. But if I tell you the\n"
"same for 1588522601 you will spend alot of time (or CPU cycles) to find it was\n"
"49811*31891. And if this number is really really big this task becomes\n"
"\"impossible\". So now if I give the world my large number that is the product of\n"
"two primes I know something about that number that no one else knows.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:838
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This is the basis for Public Key Cryptography (PKC) implementations today. As an\n"
"(unrealistic) example, I give anyone my number and that someone will use if for \n"
"cyphering a message to me. Anyone can see the cyphered message, because I am \n"
"the only one who knows a shortcut to read it, anyone else will first have to \n"
"\"split\" that big number to be able to read the message, and it is a \"fact\" \n"
"that it is impossible to do that in a short amount of time (todays methods and \n"
"the fastest computers in the world would take thousands of years to do that). \n"
"In this setup the two large prime numbers would be called the PRIVATE KEY, and \n"
"the large non prime number is the PUBLIC KEY.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:850
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In practice this is not 100% accurate with reality, but will give a good idea to\n"
"the newcomer. For more information, check Wikipedia on the <uri\n"
"link=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie-Hellman\">Diffie-Hellman</uri>\n"
"protocol. For even more info go to the public library and grab a copy of the\n"
"<uri link=\"http://www.cacr.math.uwaterloo.ca/hac/\">\"Handbook of Applied\n"
"Cryptography\"</uri> by Alfred J. Menezes, Paul C. van Oorschot and Scott A.\n"
"Vanstone. This book is also available online for free at the above site.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:860
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"One consequence of the above is that if you cypher a message to me, and you\n"
"loose the original uncyphered message you will no longer be able to retrieve it\n"
"from the cyphered version.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:868
#, no-wrap
msgid "Signatures"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:872
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"We already saw how someone can send us a cyphered message if they have our\n"
"public key. But how do we know that the author of the message is really who he\n"
"claims to be? Or in other words: If I receive an email from you how do I really\n"
"know it was you and not someone else claiming to be you? \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:879
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Remember me saying that PKC was not as simple as I had said? The idea is that\n"
"when you cypher a message to me you sign it with your private key so that, when\n"
"I receive it, I can first use your public key to check your signature and then\n"
"use my private key to decypher the message. As you can see we could not do\n"
"that in the setup I described before.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:887
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"It's also very important to sign messages so that you don't have to cypher them\n"
"beforehand. Now you can create messages that can be read by anyone, but that\n"
"come with your \"branding\". And if any single character is changed in the message\n"
"it can (and will) be detected.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:896
#, no-wrap
msgid "Key Servers and Signed Keys"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:900
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"But let's say that I have no previous contact with you until you send me a\n"
"message: how do I get your public key, and how do I really know it is yours?\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:905
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To solve this problem public Key Servers were created. When you create your key\n"
"pair (Public and Private key), you send your public key to the key server. After\n"
"this everyone can retrieve your key from there. This solves the problem of\n"
"finding the key. But how do I really know that that key is the author's key? For\n"
"this another concept must be introduced, and that is key signing:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:913
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Key signing means that if I have the public key of another person, and I know \n"
"<e>for sure</e> that it is really that persons key (it is my personal friend, \n"
"someone I know in real life, etc.) I can sign that public key and send it to \n"
"keyservers, that way I am telling the world: \"This key really belongs to the \n"
"person it claims to belong.\". That way persons that have my public key and \n"
"trust me can use that trust to trust other keys.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:922
#, no-wrap
msgid "This can sometimes be confusing so let's see a real world situation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:926
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Let's imagine a 3 person situation: John, Mary, and Lisa. John is a good\n"
"friend of Mary but does not know Lisa; Lisa is a good friend of Mary but\n"
"does not know John. One day Lisa sends John a signed email. John will fetch\n"
"Lisa's Public Key from the keyserver and test the message, if all went ok he\n"
"will see that whoever wrote that message also created that key. But how do I\n"
"know it was really the person it claims to be?\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/gnupg-user.xml:935
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"He then sees that it is signed by Mary, which he can check because he already\n"
"has Mary's key and he trusts that key. With this ring of trust he continues to\n"
"conclude that the email he received was really written by Lisa.\n"
msgstr ""

